  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers interview two or three agents, choose the one they like most, and hope for the best. The agents know this, so the listing pitch is optimised for likability: a strong headline price, a confident tone, a polished presentation folder, a few testimonials, and an ask for the signature on the Form 6 before the meeting ends. By the time the campaign is underway, the seller often realises the agent they chose was good at pitching, not necessarily good at selling.</p>

      <p>The gap between a good and average agent on a $1 million sale is routinely $30,000 to $60,000 in the final result. That makes agent selection the single highest-leverage decision a seller makes, ahead of preparation, pricing, and marketing strategy. This article sets out a structured way to rank and evaluate Brisbane agents using public data, client reviews, and a focused interview process, so the choice is based on evidence rather than personality alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The sources of public data</h2>
      <p>Agent performance is more transparent than most sellers realise. Several public sources allow you to cross-check an agent's claims before you sit down for the first meeting.</p>

      <p><strong>realestate.com.au 'Find an Agent':</strong> shows sales history by suburb, average sale price achieved, average days on market, and a volume indicator for the last 12 months. The data is reported to the portal by the agency, so it reflects listings where that agent is named as the primary or secondary agent.</p>

      <p><strong>domain.com.au agent profiles:</strong> similar sales history and suburb-level performance data. Useful as a cross-check against realestate.com.au because the two portals sometimes diverge on attribution for team sales.</p>

      <p><strong>RateMyAgent:</strong> client reviews and ratings, with a volume-weighted 'top agent' leaderboard by suburb. Reviews are verified against transactions, so the sample tends to be genuine clients rather than random commenters, though it skews towards sellers who had good outcomes.</p>

      <p><strong>Agency websites:</strong> often publish a 'recently sold' archive, a 'meet the team' section with agent biographies, and a client-testimonial page. Useful for getting a sense of the agent's self-presentation and the properties they are actively working on.</p>

      <p><strong>REIQ membership and awards:</strong> the Real Estate Institute of Queensland maintains a public register of members, and industry awards (REIQ awards, RateMyAgent awards, agency-level awards) indicate peer recognition, though they are generally correlated with sales volume rather than per-sale quality.</p>

      <p><strong>Google reviews and LinkedIn:</strong> Google reviews on the agency or agent page can surface feedback that does not appear on the specialist review platforms. LinkedIn gives a sense of professional background and tenure in real estate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the data tells you</h2>
      <p>With the sources above, you can build a structured profile of each agent on the shortlist. The key metrics, and what they mean, are:</p>

      <p><strong>Number of sales in your specific suburb in the last 12 months.</strong> This is the clearest indicator of local market knowledge. An agent who has sold 12 homes in Morningside in the past year has direct, current experience of the buyer pool, the active listings, and the sale patterns in that micro-market. An agent with two Morningside sales in the same period is operating with less data and less leverage.</p>

      <p><strong>Median sale price achieved in your price bracket.</strong> Compare this to the suburb median and to the agent's own claims. If the agent's median sale in Camp Hill is $1.15 million and the suburb median is $1.1 million, they are generally achieving slightly above market. If the agent's median is $1.0 million, the campaigns they are running are settling below the suburb median, which may indicate softer campaigns or a bias towards quick sales.</p>

      <p><strong>Average days on market.</strong> Shorter is usually better, but should be read alongside sale price. An agent with a 21-day average DOM at $1.2 million median is outperforming an agent with a 14-day average DOM at $1.05 million median, even though the second looks quicker on a first glance. Fast sales are not valuable in isolation.</p>

      <p><strong>Consistency of outcomes.</strong> Look at the distribution of sales, not just the headline averages. An agent with a tight band of sales (most within 10 per cent of the suburb median) is delivering reliable campaigns. An agent with a wide spread, a few standout sales and many significantly below median, may be relying on presentation-for-pitch rather than repeatable execution.</p>

      <p><strong>Volume over time.</strong> Cross-reference the last 12 months against the last three years. A newly emerged agent with 15 sales in the past year but none before is either a rising performer or the beneficiary of a team environment. An agent with steady volume over three years is more likely to sustain performance through different market conditions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the data hides</h2>
      <p>Public data is a filter, not a conclusion. Several limitations need to be kept in mind.</p>

      <p><strong>Market conditions shape the numbers.</strong> A strong sales record in a rising market is easier than in a flat or falling one. Compare agents to their peers operating in the same market conditions, not to historical benchmarks. An agent whose median sale price rose 12 per cent last year may simply be riding a market that moved that much.</p>

      <p><strong>Headline numbers mask the distribution.</strong> Agent profiles tend to showcase best-in-class results prominently and bury the struggles. A 'record sale on Oxford Street' is news. Three campaigns that sat on the market for 10 weeks and eventually settled below expectation are not. Look at the full list of sales, not the highlights.</p>

      <p><strong>Team attribution is fuzzy.</strong> At larger agencies, sales listed under a senior agent's profile may have been primarily managed by a junior team member. Ask directly whether the quoted sales were personally managed, negotiated, and closed by the agent you are interviewing. The answer matters.</p>

      <p><strong>Average sale price can be distorted by segment mix.</strong> An agent who sells in a mix of $600,000 units and $1.4 million houses has an average sale price somewhere in the middle that is not representative of either segment. Filter the data to your property type and price band before drawing conclusions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What client reviews tell you</h2>
      <p>Reviews on RateMyAgent, Google, and agency sites are useful but need to be read analytically. A 4.8-star average across 50 reviews tells you less than the themes that repeat across those 50 reviews.</p>

      <p><strong>Communication style:</strong> consistent positive commentary on communication (returns calls, provides weekly updates, explains offers clearly) is a strong signal. Sellers who had a good outcome but complain about communication indicate an agent who closes deals but leaves clients in the dark during the campaign.</p>

      <p><strong>Attention to preparation:</strong> reviews that mention advice on presentation, styling, repairs, or photography suggest an agent who invests in the campaign inputs, not just the listing moment.</p>

      <p><strong>Handling of negotiations:</strong> reviews that describe a thoughtful, disciplined negotiation process (rather than 'they got us the sale') indicate an agent with negotiation craft. The best reviews come from both sides of the transaction, where available.</p>

      <p><strong>How complaints are handled:</strong> a few negative reviews among many positive ones is normal. What matters is whether the agent has responded publicly to the complaint, acknowledged the issue, and explained how they addressed it. That response tells you how they are likely to handle a difficult moment in your campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do beyond the data</h2>
      <p>Once the public data has narrowed the shortlist to three to five candidates, the interview process carries the weight. Interview each in person, preferably at your property. Allocate 45 to 60 minutes. Prepare a short list of questions and take notes.</p>

      <p>Ask each agent for their last five comparable sales in your suburb, with addresses and sale prices. Cross-check these against realestate.com.au after the meeting. Discrepancies matter.</p>

      <p>Ask each for their proposed marketing strategy and price range, with the reasoning. A well-prepared agent will reference specific comparable sales, specific buyer cohorts, and a specific sequence of events (preparation period, launch week, inspection cadence, expected offer timing). An underprepared agent will speak in generalities.</p>

      <p>Get references. Ask for contact details of two or three recent clients and speak to them directly. Ask those clients the same questions you asked the agent, particularly around communication during the campaign and the handling of negotiations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The questions that reveal the most</h2>
      <p>A handful of questions tend to produce the most informative answers across a comparison of agents.</p>

      <p><strong>'Walk me through your last disappointing sale. What went wrong?'</strong> Honest agents can answer this clearly, without defensiveness, and explain what they learned. Agents who claim they have never had a disappointing sale are either inexperienced or presenting a version of themselves that will not survive the first hard week of your campaign.</p>

      <p><strong>'What would you change about the campaign if the first two weeks underperform?'</strong> Tests strategic flexibility. A good agent has a mental playbook for underperformance: refresh photography, adjust the messaging, address pricing, review the inspection process. An agent who cannot answer this is likely to default to blaming the market or pressing for a price cut.</p>

      <p><strong>'How will you communicate during the campaign?'</strong> Sets clear expectations. The agents who commit to a specific cadence (written weekly update, phone call after each open home, prompt update on every offer) are the ones who will actually deliver it. Vague answers correlate with vague communication later.</p>

      <p><strong>'What is your assessment of the risks to this campaign?'</strong> Reveals whether the agent has thought about the downside. A useful answer identifies two or three specific risks (comparable listings coming on, seasonality, a presentation item, a finance timeline) and explains how they would manage each.</p>

      <p><strong>'How do you set the price guide or listing price?'</strong> Good agents reference recent comparable sales, current competing listings, the buyer pool they are working with, and their sense of the market direction. Poor agents quote a number without structure and push you to accept it quickly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Red flags to watch for</h2>
      <p>A few signals, in the interview or the public data, warrant pause.</p>

      <p><strong>Commission-focused pitch with little detail on strategy.</strong> An agent who leads with their commission percentage, then spends more time on fees than on the campaign, is pitching a transaction rather than a result.</p>

      <p><strong>Vague claims about 'our database' or 'my buyer list'.</strong> Useful agents can tell you how many active buyers they have in your price bracket, how they gather and maintain that information, and how they will match buyers to your property. Unspecified claims are often empty.</p>

      <p><strong>Pressure to sign the Form 6 in the initial meeting.</strong> The Form 6 is the agency authority, and it runs typically for 60 to 90 days. Signing it in the first meeting removes your ability to take a second or third opinion, and it is a signal that the agent is more focused on locking in the listing than on earning it.</p>

      <p><strong>An unrealistically high appraisal.</strong> Some agents deliberately inflate their price appraisal to win the listing, then push for a price reduction two weeks into the campaign once buyers have not appeared. Compare each agent's appraisal to the public comparable sales you have already gathered. A figure significantly above the comparables needs a specific, credible justification.</p>

      <p><strong>No honest discussion of preparation.</strong> Agents who suggest your home is already 'looking great' without any recommendations for preparation are telling you what you want to hear. Every home has something to do before listing, and the agent who names two or three specific preparation items is the one who has actually looked.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Use public data to shortlist three to five candidates who have demonstrable local experience at your price point. Use structured interviews to assess strategic thinking, communication style, and honesty. Use references and reviews to verify the claims. Choose the agent whose track record matches your property and whose approach aligns with your priorities, not the one whose pitch is smoothest.</p>

      <p>A good agent earns their commission many times over in a well-run campaign. A wrong-fit agent costs tens of thousands in a poorly run one. The few hours spent on structured evaluation, before the Form 6 is signed, are among the highest-return hours of the entire sale process.</p>

